020/04/the-batman-sopranos-prequel-tom-elvis-presley-movie-warner-bros-release-dates-changes-coronavirus-1202912605/ |title='The Batman' Flies To Fall 2021, 'Sopranos' Prequel Moves To March & More As Warner Bros. Makes Release Date Changes Due To COVID-19 Climate |last=D'Alessandro |first=Anthony |website=[[Deadline Hollywood]] |date=April 20, 2020 |access-date=April 20, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200420202338/https://deadline.com/2020/04/the-batman-sopranos-prequel-tom-elvis-presley-movie-warner-bros-release-dates-changes-coronavirus-1202912605/ |archive-date=April 20, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n<!-- FUTURE -->\n\n<ref name=\"DCFilmsFutureNov2019\">{{Cite web |url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/dc-comics-superman-michael-b-jordan-green-lantern-aquaman-birds-of-prey-1203415757/ |title=DC Films Plots Future With Superman, Green Lantern and R-Rated Movies (Exclusive) |last1=Lang |first1=Brent |last2=Kroll |first2=Justin |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=November 26, 2019 |access-date=November 26, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191126172333/https://variety.com/2019/film/news/dc-comics-superman-michael-b-jordan-green-lantern-aquaman-birds-of-prey-1203415757/ |archive-date=November 26, 2019 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb title|1877830|The Batman}}\n\n{{Batman in popular media}}\n{{Catwoman}}\n{{DC Comics films}}\n{{DC Extended Universe}}\n{{Matt Reeves}}\n{{Portal bar|Film|United States|Speculative fiction}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Batman (film), The}}\n[[Category:2020s action thriller films]]\n[[Category:2020s superhero films]]\n[[Category:2020s vigilante films]]\n[[Category:2021 films]]\n[[Category:American detective films]]\n[[Category:American films]]\n[[Category:American superhero films]]\n[[Category:American vigilante films]]\n[[Category:Batman films]]\n[[Category:DC Extended Universe films]]\n[[Category:English-language films]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Matt Reeves]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Michael Giacchino]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Films shot in London]]\n[[Category:Films shot in Merseyside]]\n[[Category:Reboot films]]\n[[Category:Upcoming films]]\n[[Category:Warner Bros. films]]\n", "name_user": "179.111.25.94", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Batman_(film)"}
{"title_page": "William Walwyn", "text_new": "[[File:William Walwyn.jpg|thumb|William Walwyn]]\n'''William Walwyn''' (''bap.'' 1600\u20131681) was an English pamphleteer, a [[Leveller]] and a medical practitioner.<ref>David Plant, [http://www.british-civil-wars.co.uk/biog/walwyn.htm William Walwyn, Leveller, c. 1600\u201381 ], [http://www.british-civil-wars.co.uk/index.htm British Civil Wars & Commonwealth website], Retrieved 8 July 2009</ref><ref>Barbara Taft, \"Walwyn, William (bap. 1600, d. 1681)\", Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, Sept 2004; online edn, Oct 2008 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/28661, accessed 8 July 2009]</ref>\n\n==Life==\nWalwyn was a silkman in London who took the parliamentary side in the [[English Civil War]]. He advocated religious toleration and emerged as a leader of the [[Levellers]] in 1647, which led to his imprisonment in 1649. \n\nIn October 1645 Walwyn published ''England's Lamentable Slaverie'', his famous rebuke to John Lilburne, in which he criticised his fellow Leveller for a misguided reliance on the Magna Carta of 1225 as the foundation for citizens' rights. He argued that it was, \"more precious in your [Liliburne's] esteem than it deserveth\", dismissing it as a small set of concessions \"wrestled out of the pawes\" of Norman conquerors and describing it as, \"a messe of pottage\", and (in the following year), \"but a beggerly thing containing many marks of intollerable bondage\". Walwyn's critique of the appeal to Magna Carta was compelling and fundamentally accurate, and instead he proposed a fresh charter, a proto-social contract based in equity and right reason, rather than on compromised accretions of the law.<ref>Foxley, Rachel. \u201c\u2018More Precious in Your Esteem than It Deserveth\u2019?: Magna Carta and Seventeenth-Century Politics.\u201d ''Magna Carta: History, Context and Influence'', edited by Lawrence Goldman, University of London Press, London, 2018, pp. 61\u201378, pp.72-73. ''JSTOR'', www.jstor.org/stable/j.ctv5136sc.12. Accessed 20 Apr. 2020.</ref>  \n\nDuring 1646 he wrote five pamphlets in response to [[Thomas Edwards (heresiographer)|Thomas Edwards']] [[Gangraena]], in which Walwyn was described as \"a [[Seekers|Seeker]], a dangerous man, a strong head\". In 1649, whilst held in the [[Tower of London]] on a charge of [[Treason]], he published \"The Fountain of Slaunder Discovered\" and \"Walwyns Just Defence\" to defend his character against the publication of \"Walwyn's Wiles\".<ref name=\"Lee\">[[Sidney Lee|Lee, Sidney]] (1903), [[Dictionary of National Biography]] [https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati00leesuoft Index and Epitome], [https://archive.org/stream/dictionaryofnati00leesuoft#page/1364/mode/1up p. 1364] (also main entry lix 284)</ref><ref>Walwym is sometimes confused with William Walwyn who was appointed canon of St. Paul's, London, in 1660, but is not the same man. (Lee, Dictionary of National Biography Index and Epitome (1903))</ref> The pamphlet had seven authors who were the leading Baptist and Independent preachers in London at the time Arnald, Burnet, Foster, [[William Kiffin|Kiffin]], Lordall, Price, and Rosier, but was mainly drafted by John Price who had previously attacked Walwyn in print after four of the Leveller petitions were burnt by the common hangman in June 1647 (see \"Gold Tried in the Fire\"). In Price's opinion it was Walwyn, not Lilburne, who was the most dangerous of the [[Leveller]] leaders.<ref>{{cite book|author1=William Walwyn|author2=Jack R. McMichael|author3=Barbara Taft|title=The Writings of William Walwyn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5WlhQgAACAAJ|accessdate=23 July 2012|year=1989|publisher=University of Georgia Press|isbn=978-0-8203-1017-6}}</ref> In 1653, when [[John Lilburne|Lilburne]] was arrested having returned from exile in [[Bruges]], [[Richard Overton (pamphleteer)|Overton]] and Prince rallied support, Walwyn however was arrested and held in the [[Tower of London|tower]] until after [[John_Lilburne#Return.2C_trial_and_imprisonment|Lilburne's trial]] was concluded.<ref>{{cite book|author=Henry No\u00ebl Brailsford|title=The Levellers and the English Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oZ-aAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA616|accessdate=23 July 2012|year=1961|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-0095-5|page=616}}</ref>\n\nWilliam Walwyn died in 1681 and was buried in the [[New_Churchyard|New Churchyard, Bethlem]], where [[John Lilburne]] and other members of the Walwyn family were also buried.<ref>Robert Hartle, with Niamh Carty, Michael Henderson, Elizabeth L Knox and Don Walker ''The New Churchyard: from Moorfields marsh to Bethlem burial ground, Brokers Row and Liverpool Street'' London: Crossrail (2017) p.39</ref>\n\n==Walwyn's Wiles==\n\nThis pamphlet was written by seven of the leading London Independent and Baptist preachers and published whilst Walwyn and the other Leveller leaders were held in the [[Tower of London|tower]]. The full title was \"Walwyn's Wiles, or the Manifestators manifested, ... declaring the subtle and crafy wiles, the atheistical, blasphemous soul-murdering principles and practices of Mr William Walwyn\". Walwyn's Wiles was a response to the jointly signed Leveller pamphlet \"A Manifestation\" (April 14, 1649) which whilst it denied that they intended to level men's estates also stood firm on the principles outlined in ''[[The Agreement of the People]]''. \n\nIn the ten pages of ''Wiles'' Walwyn is variously described as a [[Jesuit]], a [[bigamist]], of having persuaded a woman to commit suicide, and that he would \"destroy all government\", that he had said \"that it would never be well until all things were common\", and that he had also said that there would be \"no need for judges ... take any other tradesman that is an honest and just man and let him hear the case\".\n\nIn response Walwyn published two pamphlets \"The Fountain of Slaunder Discovered\" in which he defended his morality, and which had written a year before but held back from publication. The second pamphlet was a direct response to ''Wiles'' as its full title \"Walwyns Just Defence against the Aspertions Cast upon him, in a Late Un-Christian Pamphlet Entitled, Walwyns Wiles\" makes clear. The ''Just Defence'' contains a great deal of detail of the Leveller movement and the Independents from 1646 onwards.\n\n==Works==\n\nPolitical and Religious Writing\n* A New Petition of the Papists 1641\n* Some Considerations Tending to the Undeceiving Those, Whose Judgements Are Misinformed 1642\n* The Power of Love 1643\n* The Compassionate Samaritane 1644\n* Good Counsell to All 1644\n* A Help to the Right Understanding of a Discourse Concerning Independency 1644/5\n* [http://www.british-civil-wars.co.uk/texts/englands-lamentable-slaverie.htm Englands Lamentable Slaverie] 1645\n* [http://www.constitution.org/lev/eng_lev_02.htm Tolleration Justified and Persecution Condemned] 1645/6\n* A Whisper in the Eare of Mr. Thomas Edwards, Minister 1645/6\n* A Word More to Mr Thomas Edwards ... Concerning the National Covenant 1645/6\n* A Word in Season: To All Sorts of Well Minded People 1646\n* An Antidote against Master Edwards 1646\n* The Just Man in Bonds 1646\n* [http://www.constitution.org/lev/eng_lev_04.htm A Remonstrance of many Thousand Citizens] (a collaboration with [[Richard Overton (pamphleteer)|Richard Overton]]) 1646\n* A Prediction of Mr Edwards His Conversion and Recantation 1646\n* A Demurre to the Bill for Preventing the Growth and Spreading of Heresie 1646\n* A Parable, or Consultation of Physitians upon Master Edwards 1646\n* [http://www.strecorsoc.org/docs/walwyn.html A Still and Soft Voice from the Scripture] 1647\n* [http://www.constitution.org/lev/eng_lev_06.htm Gold Tried in the Fire; or, The Burnt Petitions Revived] 1647\n* [http://www.strecorsoc.org/docs/project.html The Bloody Project] 1648\n* The Vanitie of the Present Churches 1648/9\n* [http://www.constitution.org/lev/eng_lev_11.htm A Manifestation] (jointly signed) 1649\n* [http://www.constitution.org/eng/agreepeo.htm An Agreement of the Free People of England] (jointly signed) 1649\n* The Fountain of Slaunder Discovered 1649\n* Walwyns Just Defence 1649\n* Juries Justified 1651\n* W Walwyns Conceptions; For a Free Trade 1652\n\nMedical Writing\n* Spirits Moderated 1654\n* Healths New Store-House Opened 1661\n* A Touch-Stone for Physick 1667\n* A Physick for Families 1669\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n;Attribution\n{{DNBIE|title=Walwyn, William|page=1364}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walwyn, William}}\n[[Category:1600s births]]\n[[Category:1681 deaths]]\n[[Category:Levellers]]\n[[Category:17th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:17th-century male writers]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:William Walwyn.jpg|thumb|William Walwyn]]\n'''William Walwyn''' (''bap.'' 1600\u20131681) was an English pamphleteer, a [[Leveller]] and a medical practitioner.<ref>David Plant, [http://www.british-civil-wars.co.uk/biog/walwyn.htm William Walwyn, Leveller, c. 1600\u201381 ], [http://www.british-civil-wars.co.uk/index.htm British Civil Wars & Commonwealth website], Retrieved 8 July 2009</ref><ref>Barbara Taft, \"Walwyn, William (bap. 1600, d. 1681)\", Oxford Dictionary of National Biography, Oxford University Press, Sept 2004; online edn, Oct 2008 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/28661, accessed 8 July 2009]</ref>\n\n==Life==\nWalwyn was a silkman in London who took the parliamentary side in the [[English Civil War]]. He advocated religious toleration and emerged as a leader of the [[Levellers]] in 1647, which led to his imprisonment in 1649. \n\nIn October 1645 Walwyn published ''England's Lamentable Slaverie'', his famous rebuke to John Lilburne, in which he criticised his fellow Leveller for a misguided reliance on the Magna Carta of 1225 as the foundation for citizens' rights. He argued that it was, \"more precious in your [Liliburne's] esteem than it deserveth\", dismissing it as a small set of concessions \"wrestled out of the pawes\" of Norman conquerors and describing it as, \"a messe of pottage\", and (in the following year), \"but a beggerly thing containing many marks of intollerable bondage\". Walwyn's critique of the appeal to Magna Carta was compelling and fundamentally accurate, and instead he proposed a fresh charter, a proto-social contract based in equity and right reason rather than on compromised accretions of the law.<ref>Foxley, Rachel. \u201c\u2018More Precious in Your Esteem than It Deserveth\u2019?: Magna Carta and Seventeenth-Century Politics.\u201d ''Magna Carta: History, Context and Influence'', edited by Lawrence Goldman, University of London Press, London, 2018, pp. 61\u201378, pp.72-73. ''JSTOR'', www.jstor.org/stable/j.ctv5136sc.12. Accessed 20 Apr. 2020.</ref>  \n\nDuring 1646 he wrote five pamphlets in response to [[Thomas Edwards (heresiographer)|Thomas Edwards']] [[Gangraena]], in which Walwyn was described as \"a [[Seekers|Seeker]], a dangerous man, a strong head\". In 1649, whilst held in the [[Tower of London]] on a charge of [[Treason]], he published \"The Fountain of Slaunder Discovered\" and \"Walwyns Just Defence\" to defend his character against the publication of \"Walwyn's Wiles\".<ref name=\"Lee\">[[Sidney Lee|Lee, Sidney]] (1903), [[Dictionary of National Biography]] [https://archive.org/details/dictionaryofnati00leesuoft Index and Epitome], [https://archive.org/stream/dictionaryofnati00leesuoft#page/1364/mode/1up p. 1364] (also main entry lix 284)</ref><ref>Walwym is sometimes confused with William Walwyn who was appointed canon of St. Paul's, London, in 1660, but is not the same man. (Lee, Dictionary of National Biography Index and Epitome (1903))</ref> The pamphlet had seven authors who were the leading Baptist and Independent preachers in London at the time Arnald, Burnet, Foster, [[William Kiffin|Kiffin]], Lordall, Price, and Rosier, but was mainly drafted by John Price who had previously attacked Walwyn in print after four of the Leveller petitions were burnt by the common hangman in June 1647 (see \"Gold Tried in the Fire\"). In Price's opinion it was Walwyn, not Lilburne, who was the most dangerous of the [[Leveller]] leaders.<ref>{{cite book|author1=William Walwyn|author2=Jack R. McMichael|author3=Barbara Taft|title=The Writings of William Walwyn|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=5WlhQgAACAAJ|accessdate=23 July 2012|year=1989|publisher=University of Georgia Press|isbn=978-0-8203-1017-6}}</ref> In 1653, when [[John Lilburne|Lilburne]] was arrested having returned from exile in [[Bruges]], [[Richard Overton (pamphleteer)|Overton]] and Prince rallied support, Walwyn however was arrested and held in the [[Tower of London|tower]] until after [[John_Lilburne#Return.2C_trial_and_imprisonment|Lilburne's trial]] was concluded.<ref>{{cite book|author=Henry No\u00ebl Brailsford|title=The Levellers and the English Revolution|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oZ-aAAAAIAAJ&pg=PA616|accessdate=23 July 2012|year=1961|publisher=Stanford University Press|isbn=978-0-8047-0095-5|page=616}}</ref>\n\nWilliam Walwyn died in 1681 and was buried in the [[New_Churchyard|New Churchyard, Bethlem]], where [[John Lilburne]] and other members of the Walwyn family were also buried.<ref>Robert Hartle, with Niamh Carty, Michael Henderson, Elizabeth L Knox and Don Walker ''The New Churchyard: from Moorfields marsh to Bethlem burial ground, Brokers Row and Liverpool Street'' London: Crossrail (2017) p.39</ref>\n\n==Walwyn's Wiles==\n\nThis pamphlet was written by seven of the leading London Independent and Baptist preachers and published whilst Walwyn and the other Leveller leaders were held in the [[Tower of London|tower]]. The full title was \"Walwyn's Wiles, or the Manifestators manifested, ... declaring the subtle and crafy wiles, the atheistical, blasphemous soul-murdering principles and practices of Mr William Walwyn\". Walwyn's Wiles was a response to the jointly signed Leveller pamphlet \"A Manifestation\" (April 14, 1649) which whilst it denied that they intended to level men's estates also stood firm on the principles outlined in ''[[The Agreement of the People]]''. \n\nIn the ten pages of ''Wiles'' Walwyn is variously described as a [[Jesuit]], a [[bigamist]], of having persuaded a woman to commit suicide, and that he would \"destroy all government\", that he had said \"that it would never be well until all things were common\", and that he had also said that there would be \"no need for judges ... take any other tradesman that is an honest and just man and let him hear the case\".\n\nIn response Walwyn published two pamphlets \"The Fountain of Slaunder Discovered\" in which he defended his morality, and which had written a year before but held back from publication. The second pamphlet was a direct response to ''Wiles'' as its full title \"Walwyns Just Defence against the Aspertions Cast upon him, in a Late Un-Christian Pamphlet Entitled, Walwyns Wiles\" makes clear. The ''Just Defence'' contains a great deal of detail of the Leveller movement and the Independents from 1646 onwards.\n\n==Works==\n\nPolitical and Religious Writing\n* A New Petition of the Papists 1641\n* Some Considerations Tending to the Undeceiving Those, Whose Judgements Are Misinformed 1642\n* The Power of Love 1643\n* The Compassionate Samaritane 1644\n* Good Counsell to All 1644\n* A Help to the Right Understanding of a Discourse Concerning Independency 1644/5\n* [http://www.british-civil-wars.co.uk/texts/englands-lamentable-slaverie.htm Englands Lamentable Slaverie] 1645\n* [http://www.constitution.org/lev/eng_lev_02.htm Tolleration Justified and Persecution Condemned] 1645/6\n* A Whisper in the Eare of Mr. Thomas Edwards, Minister 1645/6\n* A Word More to Mr Thomas Edwards ... Concerning the National Covenant 1645/6\n* A Word in Season: To All Sorts of Well Minded People 1646\n* An Antidote against Master Edwards 1646\n* The Just Man in Bonds 1646\n* [http://www.constitution.org/lev/eng_lev_04.htm A Remonstrance of many Thousand Citizens] (a collaboration with [[Richard Overton (pamphleteer)|Richard Overton]]) 1646\n* A Prediction of Mr Edwards His Conversion and Recantation 1646\n* A Demurre to the Bill for Preventing the Growth and Spreading of Heresie 1646\n* A Parable, or Consultation of Physitians upon Master Edwards 1646\n* [http://www.strecorsoc.org/docs/walwyn.html A Still and Soft Voice from the Scripture] 1647\n* [http://www.constitution.org/lev/eng_lev_06.htm Gold Tried in the Fire; or, The Burnt Petitions Revived] 1647\n* [http://www.strecorsoc.org/docs/project.html The Bloody Project] 1648\n* The Vanitie of the Present Churches 1648/9\n* [http://www.constitution.org/lev/eng_lev_11.htm A Manifestation] (jointly signed) 1649\n* [http://www.constitution.org/eng/agreepeo.htm An Agreement of the Free People of England] (jointly signed) 1649\n* The Fountain of Slaunder Discovered 1649\n* Walwyns Just Defence 1649\n* Juries Justified 1651\n* W Walwyns Conceptions; For a Free Trade 1652\n\nMedical Writing\n* Spirits Moderated 1654\n* Healths New Store-House Opened 1661\n* A Touch-Stone for Physick 1667\n* A Physick for Families 1669\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n;Attribution\n{{DNBIE|title=Walwyn, William|page=1364}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Walwyn, William}}\n[[Category:1600s births]]\n[[Category:1681 deaths]]\n[[Category:Levellers]]\n[[Category:17th-century English writers]]\n[[Category:17th-century male writers]]\n", "name_user": "Shtove", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eLife", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Walwyn"}
{"title_page": "Regions of Queensland", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Qld-regions-map.gif|thumb|Queensland Regions]]\n[[File:Queensland roads.svg|thumb|220px|Cities and highways in Queensland]]\n\nThe '''Regions of Queensland''' refer to the geographic areas of the Australian state of [[Queensland]]. Due to its large size and decentralised population, the state is often divided into regions for statistical and administrative purposes. Each region varies somewhat in terms of its economy, population, climate, geography, flora and fauna. Cultural and official perceptions and definitions of the various regions differ somewhat depending on the government agency or popular group by which they are being applied.\n\n== Overview ==\nVarious Queensland state government departments adopt different definitions of regions for administrative purposes. The Queensland government Trade and Investment Queensland defines seven regions. These are (roughly from south to north).\n* [[South East Queensland]]\n* Darling Downs South West\n* [[Wide Bay\u2013Burnett]]\n* [[Central Queensland]]\n* Mackay, Isaac and Whitsunday \n* [[North Queensland|Northern]]\n* [[Far North Queensland|Far North]]\nSmaller regions may also exist within these defined regions, such as the [[Torres Strait Islands]], [[Whitsunday Islands]] and [[South West Queensland]].\n\n== South East Queensland ==\n{{main|South East Queensland}}\n[[Image:Brisbane from Mt Mount Coot-tha.jpg|thumb|right|[[Brisbane]] is the largest city in both the South East Queensland region and the state of Queensland.]]\n[[File:Gold Coast traffic.jpg|thumb|The Gold Coast]]\n[[South East Queensland]] is commonly considered to be a single region. It contains two statistical regions listed above, Brisbane and Moreton. The region has a population of 3,500,000 people, or 72% of the state's population.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://planning.dsdmip.qld.gov.au/planning/better-planning/state-planning/regional-plans/seqrp |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-04-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419053326/https://planning.dsdmip.qld.gov.au/planning/better-planning/state-planning/regional-plans/seqrp |archive-date=2018-04-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> The area contains [[Brisbane]], the state's capital city, as well as the [[Logan City]], [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]], [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland|Sunshine Coast]], [[Ipswich, Queensland|Ipswich]] and the [[Lockyer Valley]]. The region is the major administrative and commercial centre and focus of tourism within Queensland.\n\nThe Brisbane region comprises the greater [[Brisbane]] metropolitan area, centred on the [[City of Brisbane]] and also including the [[Logan City|Logan]], [[Redland City|Redland]], [[Moreton Bay Region|Moreton Bay]] and [[City of Ipswich|Ipswich]] local government areas. The metropolitan area has a population of 2,360,241 (2016)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://dilgpprd.blob.core.windows.net/general/shapingseq.pdf|title=3218.0 \u2013 South East Queensland Regional Plan, Australia, 2017|author=[[Department of Infrastructure, Local Government and Planning]]|date=11 August 2017|accessdate=11 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418230237/https://dilgpprd.blob.core.windows.net/general/shapingseq.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is the state's main commercial and administrative centre and contains the state's largest domestic and international airport.\n\nThe [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold]] and [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland|Sunshine]] Coasts, located south and north of Brisbane respectively, are two of the Queensland's most popular tourist regions, containing many hotels and resorts. Each region has an airport which caters primarily to tourists. The remaining parts of the region are located inland, west of Brisbane, and are primarily rural.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.censusdata.abs.gov.au/census_services/getproduct/census/2016/quickstat/3GBRI?opendocument |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-04-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714081145/http://www.censusdata.abs.gov.au/census_services/getproduct/census/2016/quickstat/3GBRI?opendocument |archive-date=2017-07-14 |url-status=live }}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://planning.dsdmip.qld.gov.au/planning/better-planning/state-planning/regional-plans/seqrp |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-04-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419053326/https://planning.dsdmip.qld.gov.au/planning/better-planning/state-planning/regional-plans/seqrp |archive-date=2018-04-19 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Darling Downs South West ==\n{{main|Darling Downs, Queensland}}{{main|South West Queensland}}\nThe Darling Downs South West region is located about {{convert|160|km|mi|0}} west of [[Brisbane]] and borders the states of [[New South Wales]] and [[South Australia]]. The region consists of the fertile agricultural area west of the [[Great Dividing Range]] and south to the [[New South Wales]] state border, centred on the city of [[Toowoomba, Queensland|Toowoomba]]. It has an area of {{convert|410129|km2|sqmi|0}} and contains the local government areas of [[Toowoomba Region|Toowoomba]], [[Goondiwindi Region|Goondiwindi]], [[Southern Downs Region|Southern Downs]], [[Western Downs Region|Western Downs]], [[Maranoa Region|Maranoa]], [[Shire of Balonne|Balonne]], [[Shire of Bulloo|Bulloo]], [[Shire of Murweh|Murweh]], [[Shire of Paroo|Paroo]] and [[Shire of Quilpie|Quilpie]]. In 2008, the region had a population of 257,749.<ref name=ABSQ08>{{cite news|url=http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/Products/3218.0~2007-08~Main+Features~Queensland?OpenDocument|title=3218.0 \u2013 Regional Population Growth, Australia, 2007-08 \u2013 Queensland|author=[[Australian Bureau of Statistics]]|date=23 April 2009|accessdate=30 May 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120225412/http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/Products/3218.0~2007-08~Main+Features~Queensland?OpenDocument|archive-date=20 January 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Economic activities include cattle grazing, cotton farming, and natural resource extraction such as natural gas and opal mining.\n\n==Wide Bay\u2013Burnett ==\n[[Image:Hbay.JPG|thumb|right|[[Hervey Bay]] is part of the Wide Bay\u2013Burnett region]]\n{{main|Wide Bay\u2013Burnett}}\nThe Wide Bay\u2013Burnett region is located north-east of the [[Darling Downs]] and north of the [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland|Sunshine Coast]], covering a region of {{convert|52377|km2|sqmi|0}}. It consists of the [[Bundaberg Region|Bundaberg]], [[Fraser Coast Region|Fraser Coast]], [[Gympie Region|Gympie]], [[North Burnett Region|North Burnett]] and [[South Burnett Region|South Burnett]] local government areas. Major centres include [[Bundaberg]], [[Gympie]], [[Hervey Bay]], [[Kingaroy]] and [[Maryborough, Queensland|Maryborough]]. The area is rich in [[sugar cane]] farms and mills and has a significant tourism industry \u2013 it includes [[Fraser Island]], a popular tourist destination and world's largest sand island. Its population in 2008 was 276,752.<ref name=ABSQ08/>\n\n==Central Queensland==\n{{main|Central Queensland}}\n{{see also|Central West Queensland}}\nThe Central Queensland region borders [[South Australia]] and the [[Northern Territory]], and contains the major centres of [[Rockhampton]] and [[Gladstone, Queensland|Gladstone]], the coastal areas and popular holiday destinations [[Yeppoon]], [[Agnes Water]] and [[1770, Queensland|1770]], and well as the areas further west of the [[Barcaldine Region|Barcaldine]], [[Shire of Barcoo|Barcoo]], [[Blackall-Tambo Region|Blackall-Tambo]], [[Shire of Boulia|Boulia]], [[Shire of Diamantina|Diamantina]], [[Longreach Region|Longreach]] and [[Shire of Winton|Winton]] local government areas. Despite its vast land area of {{convert|497714|km2|sqmi|0}}, it only had a population of 200,172 (2008). The region's economy is heavily dominated by coal mining, and cattle grazing. A major [[aluminium]] smelter is located in Gladstone. \n\n===Mackay, Isaac & Whitsunday===\nThe Mackay, Isaac & Whitsunday region is centred on the coastal city of [[Mackay, Queensland|Mackay]] and extends some 300&nbsp;km inland. It contains the [[Whitsunday Islands]] group and the coastal towns of [[Proserpine, Queensland|Proserpine]], [[Bowen, Queensland|Bowen]] and [[Sarina, Queensland|Sarina]]. The coastal areas are densely covered in sugar cane farms, while the less densely populated inland areas have several mining communities.\n\n== North Queensland ==\n{{Main|North Queensland}}\nThe North Queensland region is a coastal region centered on the city of [[Townsville]] and secondary inland city of [[Mount Isa]]. Townsville is the location of a major [[seaport]] handling exports from mines in [[Mount Isa]] and cattle exports from coastal and inland areas. The region also contains a bulk sugar exporting terminal at [[Lucinda, Queensland|Lucinda]] in the region's north. Other inland towns include [[Charters Towers, Queensland|Charters Towers]] and [[Cloncurry, Queensland|Cloncurry]], and the coastal towns of [[Ayr, Queensland|Ayr]], [[Home Hill, Queensland|Home Hill]] and [[Ingham, Queensland|Ingham]].\n\n==Far North==\n[[Image:Hinchinbrook Island.jpg|thumb|right|Tropical rainforests and beaches on [[Hinchinbrook Island]]]]\n{{main|Far North Queensland}}\nThe Far North region is Queensland's largest region covering 22% of the state's area and includes [[Cape York Peninsula]], the [[Torres Strait]], and at the [[Gulf of Carpentaria]]. The main population and administrative centre of the region is located in [[Cairns]]. Other key population centres include [[Cooktown, Queensland|Cooktown]], the [[Atherton Tableland]], [[Weipa, Queensland|Weipa]], [[Normanton, Queensland|Normanton]], and [[Thursday Island]]. The region also consists of many Aboriginal and farming communities. The region covers an area of {{convert|380,748.3|km2|sqmi|0}} and in 2012 the region's population was 301,256 of which 146,778 lived in Cairns.<ref name=ABSQ08/> Significant industries include tourism, cattle grazing, agriculture (sugar cane and tropical fruits) and mining of both sand and bauxite. \n[[Image:Lawn Hill Gorge.JPG|thumb|right|Lawn Hill Gorge in [[Boodjamulla National Park]]]]\n\n== Other definitions ==\nOther names for regions are in popular usage, for example by different government agencies and in various regional maps of Queensland. The state also contains smaller regions within those discussed above which are not necessarily used for statistical purposes, but which are distinct in terms of their geography, economy or demographic characteristics. Such regions in Queensland include: \n* [[Tropical Queensland]] \u2013 the area of the state north of latitude 23.5 degrees South.\n* Tropical North Queensland \u2013 an area of tropical Queensland that usually includes [[Far North Queensland]], and sometimes also [[North Queensland]].\n* The [[Outback]] \u2013 refers generally to Australian arid inland regions.\n* [[Whitsunday Islands]] \u2013 a group of islands in the Mackay region. A popular tourist destination, the name usually includes the coastal community of [[Airlie Beach, Queensland|Airlie Beach]], and sometimes also [[Proserpine, Queensland|Proserpine]].\n* [[Torres Strait Islands]] \u2013 islands between the northern tip of Queensland and [[Papua New Guinea]]\n* [[Atherton Tableland]] \u2013 a fertile agricultural district in the Cairns hinterland, [[Far North Queensland]].\n* [[Granite Belt]] \u2013 an area of south-east Queensland centred on the town of [[Stanthorpe, Queensland|Stanthorpe]].\n* [[Border Rivers (Australia)|Border Rivers]] \u2013 an area near the border of New South Wales and Queensland.\n* [[Capricorn Coast]] \u2013 a section of the Central Queensland coastline near the [[Tropic of Capricorn]].\n* [[Maranoa, Queensland|Maranoa]] \u2013 a district that is sometimes referred to as the ''Western Darling Downs'', in [[South West Queensland]].\n* [[The Marlin Coast]] \u2013 a coastal area centered on [[Cairns]].\n* [[North West Queensland]] \u2013 the area around [[Mt Isa]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Queensland}}\n* [[List of regions in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n#{{note|ATSIpopulation }} [http://www.oesr.qld.gov.au/data/briefs/demography/census_2001/atsi_demography_c01.pdf Office of Economic and Statistical research \u2013 Aborisginal and Torres Strait Islander population]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n#{{note|ABS4}} [http://www.ausstats.abs.gov.au/Ausstats/free.nsf/Lookup/D9521D857DF9BC16CA256E6E00009529/$File/NRP_355.xls Australian Bureau of Statistics \u2013 North West regional profile].\n#{{note|ABS5}} [http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/free.nsf/log?openagent&NRP%5F315%2Exls&315&National%20Regional%20Profile&F963FBFC97BCD104CA256E6E00005EF1&0&2003&29%2E03%2E2005&Current Australian Bureau of Statistics \u2013 Wide Bay-Burnet divisional profile]\n{{Queensland}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.business.qld.gov.au/invest/queenslands-regional-locations/map-of-queensland-regions]\n\n[[Category:Regions of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Regions of Australia]]\nLook at dis d00d\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n[[File:Qld-regions-map.gif|thumb|Queensland Regions]]\n[[File:Queensland roads.svg|thumb|220px|Cities and highways in Queensland]]\n\nThe '''Regions of Queensland''' refer to the geographic areas of the Australian state of [[Queensland]]. Due to its large size and decentralised population, the state is often divided into regions for statistical and administrative purposes. Each region varies somewhat in terms of its economy, population, climate, geography, flora and fauna. Cultural and official perceptions and definitions of the various regions differ somewhat depending on the government agency or popular group by which they are being applied.\n\n== Overview ==\nVarious Queensland state government departments adopt different definitions of regions for administrative purposes. The Queensland government Trade and Investment Queensland defines seven regions. These are (roughly from south to north).\n* [[South East Queensland]]\n* Darling Downs South West\n* [[Wide Bay\u2013Burnett]]\n* [[Central Queensland]]\n* Mackay, Isaac and Whitsunday \n* [[North Queensland|Northern]]\n* [[Far North Queensland|Far North]]\nSmaller regions may also exist within these defined regions, such as the [[Torres Strait Islands]], [[Whitsunday Islands]] and [[South West Queensland]].\n\n== South East Queensland ==\n{{main|South East Queensland}}\n[[Image:Brisbane from Mt Mount Coot-tha.jpg|thumb|right|[[Brisbane]] is the largest city in both the South East Queensland region and the state of Queensland.]]\n[[File:Gold Coast traffic.jpg|thumb|The Gold Coast]]\n[[South East Queensland]] is commonly considered to be a single region. It contains two statistical regions listed above, Brisbane and Moreton. The region has a population of 3,500,000 people, or 72% of the state's population.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://planning.dsdmip.qld.gov.au/planning/better-planning/state-planning/regional-plans/seqrp |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-04-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419053326/https://planning.dsdmip.qld.gov.au/planning/better-planning/state-planning/regional-plans/seqrp |archive-date=2018-04-19 |url-status=live }}</ref> The area contains [[Brisbane]], the state's capital city, as well as the [[Logan City]], [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold Coast]], [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland|Sunshine Coast]], [[Ipswich, Queensland|Ipswich]] and the [[Lockyer Valley]]. The region is the major administrative and commercial centre and focus of tourism within Queensland.\n\nThe Brisbane region comprises the greater [[Brisbane]] metropolitan area, centred on the [[City of Brisbane]] and also including the [[Logan City|Logan]], [[Redland City|Redland]], [[Moreton Bay Region|Moreton Bay]] and [[City of Ipswich|Ipswich]] local government areas. The metropolitan area has a population of 2,360,241 (2016)<ref>{{cite news|url=https://dilgpprd.blob.core.windows.net/general/shapingseq.pdf|title=3218.0 \u2013 South East Queensland Regional Plan, Australia, 2017|author=[[Department of Infrastructure, Local Government and Planning]]|date=11 August 2017|accessdate=11 August 2017|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180418230237/https://dilgpprd.blob.core.windows.net/general/shapingseq.pdf|archive-date=18 April 2018|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> It is the state's main commercial and administrative centre and contains the state's largest domestic and international airport.\n\nThe [[Gold Coast, Queensland|Gold]] and [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland|Sunshine]] Coasts, located south and north of Brisbane respectively, are two of the Queensland's most popular tourist regions, containing many hotels and resorts. Each region has an airport which caters primarily to tourists. The remaining parts of the region are located inland, west of Brisbane, and are primarily rural.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.censusdata.abs.gov.au/census_services/getproduct/census/2016/quickstat/3GBRI?opendocument |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-04-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170714081145/http://www.censusdata.abs.gov.au/census_services/getproduct/census/2016/quickstat/3GBRI?opendocument |archive-date=2017-07-14 |url-status=live }}</ref> <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://planning.dsdmip.qld.gov.au/planning/better-planning/state-planning/regional-plans/seqrp |title=Archived copy |access-date=2018-04-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180419053326/https://planning.dsdmip.qld.gov.au/planning/better-planning/state-planning/regional-plans/seqrp |archive-date=2018-04-19 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n== Darling Downs South West ==\n{{main|Darling Downs, Queensland}}{{main|South West Queensland}}\nThe Darling Downs South West region is located about {{convert|160|km|mi|0}} west of [[Brisbane]] and borders the states of [[New South Wales]] and [[South Australia]]. The region consists of the fertile agricultural area west of the [[Great Dividing Range]] and south to the [[New South Wales]] state border, centred on the city of [[Toowoomba, Queensland|Toowoomba]]. It has an area of {{convert|410129|km2|sqmi|0}} and contains the local government areas of [[Toowoomba Region|Toowoomba]], [[Goondiwindi Region|Goondiwindi]], [[Southern Downs Region|Southern Downs]], [[Western Downs Region|Western Downs]], [[Maranoa Region|Maranoa]], [[Shire of Balonne|Balonne]], [[Shire of Bulloo|Bulloo]], [[Shire of Murweh|Murweh]], [[Shire of Paroo|Paroo]] and [[Shire of Quilpie|Quilpie]]. In 2008, the region had a population of 257,749.<ref name=ABSQ08>{{cite news|url=http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/Products/3218.0~2007-08~Main+Features~Queensland?OpenDocument|title=3218.0 \u2013 Regional Population Growth, Australia, 2007-08 \u2013 Queensland|author=[[Australian Bureau of Statistics]]|date=23 April 2009|accessdate=30 May 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120120225412/http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/abs@.nsf/Products/3218.0~2007-08~Main+Features~Queensland?OpenDocument|archive-date=20 January 2012|url-status=live|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Economic activities include cattle grazing, cotton farming, and natural resource extraction such as natural gas and opal mining.\n\n==Wide Bay\u2013Burnett ==\n[[Image:Hbay.JPG|thumb|right|[[Hervey Bay]] is part of the Wide Bay\u2013Burnett region]]\n{{main|Wide Bay\u2013Burnett}}\nThe Wide Bay\u2013Burnett region is located north-east of the [[Darling Downs]] and north of the [[Sunshine Coast, Queensland|Sunshine Coast]], covering a region of {{convert|52377|km2|sqmi|0}}. It consists of the [[Bundaberg Region|Bundaberg]], [[Fraser Coast Region|Fraser Coast]], [[Gympie Region|Gympie]], [[North Burnett Region|North Burnett]] and [[South Burnett Region|South Burnett]] local government areas. Major centres include [[Bundaberg]], [[Gympie]], [[Hervey Bay]], [[Kingaroy]] and [[Maryborough, Queensland|Maryborough]]. The area is rich in [[sugar cane]] farms and mills and has a significant tourism industry \u2013 it includes [[Fraser Island]], a popular tourist destination and world's largest sand island. Its population in 2008 was 276,752.<ref name=ABSQ08/>\n\n==Central Queensland==\n{{main|Central Queensland}}\n{{see also|Central West Queensland}}\nThe Central Queensland region borders [[South Australia]] and the [[Northern Territory]], and contains the major centres of [[Rockhampton]] and [[Gladstone, Queensland|Gladstone]], the coastal areas and popular holiday destinations [[Yeppoon]], [[Agnes Water]] and [[1770, Queensland|1770]], and well as the areas further west of the [[Barcaldine Region|Barcaldine]], [[Shire of Barcoo|Barcoo]], [[Blackall-Tambo Region|Blackall-Tambo]], [[Shire of Boulia|Boulia]], [[Shire of Diamantina|Diamantina]], [[Longreach Region|Longreach]] and [[Shire of Winton|Winton]] local government areas. Despite its vast land area of {{convert|497714|km2|sqmi|0}}, it only had a population of 200,172 (2008). The region's economy is heavily dominated by coal mining, and cattle grazing. A major [[aluminium]] smelter is located in Gladstone. \n\n===Mackay, Isaac & Whitsunday===\nThe Mackay, Isaac & Whitsunday region is centred on the coastal city of [[Mackay, Queensland|Mackay]] and extends some 300&nbsp;km inland. It contains the [[Whitsunday Islands]] group and the coastal towns of [[Proserpine, Queensland|Proserpine]], [[Bowen, Queensland|Bowen]] and [[Sarina, Queensland|Sarina]]. The coastal areas are densely covered in sugar cane farms, while the less densely populated inland areas have several mining communities.\n\n== North Queensland ==\n{{Main|North Queensland}}\nThe North Queensland region is a coastal region centered on the city of [[Townsville]] and secondary inland city of [[Mount Isa]]. Townsville is the location of a major [[seaport]] handling exports from mines in [[Mount Isa]] and cattle exports from coastal and inland areas. The region also contains a bulk sugar exporting terminal at [[Lucinda, Queensland|Lucinda]] in the region's north. Other inland towns include [[Charters Towers, Queensland|Charters Towers]] and [[Cloncurry, Queensland|Cloncurry]], and the coastal towns of [[Ayr, Queensland|Ayr]], [[Home Hill, Queensland|Home Hill]] and [[Ingham, Queensland|Ingham]].\n\n==Far North==\n[[Image:Hinchinbrook Island.jpg|thumb|right|Tropical rainforests and beaches on [[Hinchinbrook Island]]]]\n{{main|Far North Queensland}}\nThe Far North region is Queensland's largest region covering 22% of the state's area and includes [[Cape York Peninsula]], the [[Torres Strait]], and at the [[Gulf of Carpentaria]]. The main population and administrative centre of the region is located in [[Cairns]]. Other key population centres include [[Cooktown, Queensland|Cooktown]], the [[Atherton Tableland]], [[Weipa, Queensland|Weipa]], [[Normanton, Queensland|Normanton]], and [[Thursday Island]]. The region also consists of many Aboriginal and farming communities. The region covers an area of {{convert|380,748.3|km2|sqmi|0}} and in 2012 the region's population was 301,256 of which 146,778 lived in Cairns.<ref name=ABSQ08/> Significant industries include tourism, cattle grazing, agriculture (sugar cane and tropical fruits) and mining of both sand and bauxite. \n[[Image:Lawn Hill Gorge.JPG|thumb|right|Lawn Hill Gorge in [[Boodjamulla National Park]]]]\n\n== Other definitions ==\nOther names for regions are in popular usage, for example by different government agencies and in various regional maps of Queensland. The state also contains smaller regions within those discussed above which are not necessarily used for statistical purposes, but which are distinct in terms of their geography, economy or demographic characteristics. Such regions in Queensland include: \n* [[Tropical Queensland]] \u2013 the area of the state north of latitude 23.5 degrees South.\n* Tropical North Queensland \u2013 an area of tropical Queensland that usually includes [[Far North Queensland]], and sometimes also [[North Queensland]].\n* The [[Outback]] \u2013 refers generally to Australian arid inland regions.\n* [[Whitsunday Islands]] \u2013 a group of islands in the Mackay region. A popular tourist destination, the name usually includes the coastal community of [[Airlie Beach, Queensland|Airlie Beach]], and sometimes also [[Proserpine, Queensland|Proserpine]].\n* [[Torres Strait Islands]] \u2013 islands between the northern tip of Queensland and [[Papua New Guinea]]\n* [[Atherton Tableland]] \u2013 a fertile agricultural district in the Cairns hinterland, [[Far North Queensland]].\n* [[Granite Belt]] \u2013 an area of south-east Queensland centred on the town of [[Stanthorpe, Queensland|Stanthorpe]].\n* [[Border Rivers (Australia)|Border Rivers]] \u2013 an area near the border of New South Wales and Queensland.\n* [[Capricorn Coast]] \u2013 a section of the Central Queensland coastline near the [[Tropic of Capricorn]].\n* [[Maranoa, Queensland|Maranoa]] \u2013 a district that is sometimes referred to as the ''Western Darling Downs'', in [[South West Queensland]].\n* [[The Marlin Coast]] \u2013 a coastal area centered on [[Cairns]].\n* [[North West Queensland]] \u2013 the area around [[Mt Isa]].\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Queensland}}\n* [[List of regions in Australia]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n#{{note|ATSIpopulation }} [http://www.oesr.qld.gov.au/data/briefs/demography/census_2001/atsi_demography_c01.pdf Office of Economic and Statistical research \u2013 Aborisginal and Torres Strait Islander population]{{dead link|date=April 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}\n#{{note|ABS4}} [http://www.ausstats.abs.gov.au/Ausstats/free.nsf/Lookup/D9521D857DF9BC16CA256E6E00009529/$File/NRP_355.xls Australian Bureau of Statistics \u2013 North West regional profile].\n#{{note|ABS5}} [http://www.abs.gov.au/ausstats/free.nsf/log?openagent&NRP%5F315%2Exls&315&National%20Regional%20Profile&F963FBFC97BCD104CA256E6E00005EF1&0&2003&29%2E03%2E2005&Current Australian Bureau of Statistics \u2013 Wide Bay-Burnet divisional profile]\n{{Queensland}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.business.qld.gov.au/invest/queenslands-regional-locations/map-of-queensland-regions]\n\n[[Category:Regions of Queensland]]\n[[Category:Regions of Australia]]\n", "name_user": "71.93.218.236", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Regions_of_Queensland"}
{"title_page": "Royal Golden Eagle", "text_new": "{{infobox company\n| name             = Royal Golden Eagle \n| logo             = \n| type             = [[Corporation|Private]]\n| genre            = \n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = \n| founder          = [[Sukanto Tanoto]]\n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = [[Singapore]]\n| location_country = \n| locations        = \n| area_served      = [[World]]wide\n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Pulp (paper)|Pulp]], [[paper industry|paper]], [[Rayon]]\n| products         = [[Packaging]], paper, tissue, Rayon\n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| assets           = \n| net_income       = \n| operating_income = \n| aum              = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{url|https://www.rgei.com/}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Royal Golden Eagle''' ('''RGE''', also known as '''Raja Garuda Emas''', previously '''Raja Garuda Mas''') is an integrated, resource-based industrial group in Asia Pacific, with businesses in paper, palm oil, construction and energy, property, asset management. Owned by [[Demographics of Indonesia|Indonesian]] businessman [[Sukanto Tanoto]], the group employs 60,000 people worldwide with assets exceeding [[US$]]20 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/organizations/rge-pte-ltd/|title=RGE|website=World Economic Forum|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[Sukanto Tanoto]] founded his first business in 1967 supplying spare parts to the oil and construction industries in Indonesia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sukantotanoto.net/sukantotanoto|title=RGE Group {{!}} Indonesia Founder|website=www.sukantotanoto.net|access-date=2016-11-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314064455/http://www.sukantotanoto.net/sukantotanoto|archive-date=2017-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref> before winning contracts in building gas pipelines for multinationals in 1972.<ref name=fortune2007>{{cite web |url=http://www.rgmi.com/index.php/component/option,com_docman/Itemid,/task,doc_download/gid,8 |title=From rags to US$2.8b fortune |work=The Business Times |date=2007-04-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070705183323/http://www.rgmi.com/index.php/component/option,com_docman/Itemid,/task,doc_download/gid,8 |archivedate=July 5, 2007 }}</ref> His business grew considerably following the [[1973 oil crisis]] when he open his own plywood mill in Indonesia.<ref name=\"Sukanto2009\"/> He diversified into palm oil in 1979. Since 1985, Tanoto\u2019s companies have planted 30,000 acres of palm oil plantation each year, with plantations spread over three provinces in Sumatra with a total land area of 160,000 hectares.<ref name=\"Sukanto2009\"/> He listed the public pulp and paper business [[Asia Pacific Resources International Holdings]] (APRIL) on the New York Stock Exchange in 1995, delisting it in 2001.<ref name=richest2006>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/80/06indonesia_Sukanto-Tanoto-family_USK7.html|title=Indonesia's 40 Richest 2006|work=Forbes|date=2006-07-09|access-date=2017-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204085508/http://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/80/06indonesia_Sukanto-Tanoto-family_USK7.html|archive-date=2016-12-04|url-status=live}}</ref> The company moved its base to Singapore in 1997 in order to mitigate the effects of a global travel ban that had been placed upon Indonesia at the time.<ref name=\"Sukanto2009\"/> In 2011 APRIL became a founding member of the Indonesia Business Council for Sustainable Development.<ref name=\"aprilwebsite\"/>\n\n==Business Structure==\nFrom its base in Singapore, the company conducts activities across four business sectors: pulp and paper; agro industry; dissolving wood pulp and viscose staple fibre; and energy resource development.<ref name=\"Sukanto2009\"/>\n\n===Asia Pacific Resources International Holdings Limited (APRIL)===\nLocated in the [[Riau|Riau province]] of Indonesia, [[Asia Pacific Resources International Holdings|APRIL]] operates one of the world\u2019s largest pulp and paper mills.<ref name=sustainabilitysolution>[http://www.aprilasia.com/images/pdfs/APRIL%27s%20commitment%20to%20being%20part%20of%20the%20sustainability%20solution%20-%20by%20AJ%20Devanesan,%20COO%20APRIL.pdf \"APRIL's commitment to being part of the 'sustainability solution',\"]{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Business 2020, November 2011</ref> With an annual pulp production capacity of 2.8 million tons and an annual fine paper production capacity of 820,000 tons,<ref name=rgeiapril>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/april|title=APRIL|publisher=Royal Golden Eagle|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004092531/http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/april|archive-date=2014-10-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> it generates employment opportunities for 90,000 local people and represents 6.9% of Riau Province\u2019s economic output (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aprilasia.com/images/pdfs/2011-Executive%20Summary%20Analisis%20Dampak%20in%20Bahasa%2012des%202011.pdf|title=Economic and Fiscal Impact Analysis of PT RAPP|publisher=University of Indonesia \u2013 Economic and Social Research Unit|year=2010}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Asia Symbol===\nEstablished in Shandong and Guangdong, China in 2005, Asia Symbol has an annual production capacity of 1.5 million tons of pulp, 450,000 tons of fine paper and 520,000 tons of paper board. Its Shandong plant operates the world\u2019s largest single pulp production line, with state-of-the-art manufacturing technology and environment protection practices.<ref name=rgeiasiasymbol>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/asia-symbol|title=Asia Symbol|publisher=Royal Golden Eagle|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004144610/http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/asia-symbol|archive-date=2014-10-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBoardOne (\u535a\u65fa in Chinese) is the main brand of paperboard products produced by the Shandong mill. It includes several types of packaging, including packaging for food, tobacco, and pharmaceuticals products. BoardOne can be found in Europe, Americas, ME and Asia market. BoardOne is featured with printability, and runnability on high speed packaging lines.\n\nThere are two lines producing BoardOne products. BM11 has a web width of 3.6m, grammage range of 190-380g, main products are FBB and SBS; BM12 has a web width of 4.6m, grammage range of 170-400g, mainly LPB, cigarette packaging boards and food packaging/service boards (cup stock and cup plate etc.).\n\nThere are two pulp lines located in Shandong mill. BHKP and BSKP can be supplied internally for BoardOne board making.\n\n===Asian Agri===\n[[Asian Agri]] is one of Asia\u2019s largest [[palm oil]] producers, with an annual crude palm oil production capacity of one million tons with 28 oil palm plantations, 19 palm oil mills and 160,000 hectares of palm plantation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgei.com/group-companies-sp-373/asian-agri|title=Asian Agri|publisher=Royal Golden Eagle|access-date=2014-12-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217101020/http://www.rgei.com/group-companies-sp-373/asian-agri|archive-date=2014-12-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Apical Group Limited===\n[[Apical Group|Apical]], with operations in Indonesia and China, is one Indonesia's largest exporters of palm oil with refining, processing and trading of palm oil for both domestic use and international export. The company's operations in include four refineries, a biodiesel plant and a crushing plant.<ref name=rgeiapical>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/apical|title=Apical|publisher=Royal Golden Eagle|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217100958/http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/apical|archive-date=2014-12-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Bracell Limited===\n[[Bracell Limited]] (Bracell, {{sehk|1768}}) is one of the largest specialty cellulose producers in the world. Its operations are in Brazil. It produces different grades of specialty cellulose.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bracell.com/|title=Home|website=Bracell|access-date=2019-07-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717112530/https://www.bracell.com/|archive-date=2019-07-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIt was formerly known as Sateri Holdings Limited, which undergone a name change on February 26, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brazilcellulose.com/phocadownload/download/document/bracell-completes-name-changee.pdf|title=Bracell Limited Completes Name Change|date=2015-11-02|access-date=2015-11-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055144/http://www.brazilcellulose.com/phocadownload/download/document/bracell-completes-name-changee.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref> Bracell was privatized on Oct 24, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lesprom.com/en/news/Bracell_completes_1_1_billion_privatisation_75774/|title=Bracell completes $1.1 billion privatisation|website=www.lesprom.com|access-date=2019-07-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716205318/https://www.lesprom.com/en/news/Bracell_completes_1_1_billion_privatisation_75774|archive-date=2019-07-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nRGE completed the acquisition of Lwarcel Celulose from Lwart Group on Aug 31, 2018. Lwarcel will be managed under Bracell Group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euwid-paper.com/news/singlenews/Artikel/rge-completes-lwarcel-takeover.html|title=RGE completes Lwarcel Celulose takeover &#124; EUWID Pulp and Paper|website=www.euwid-paper.com|access-date=2018-10-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018161844/https://www.euwid-paper.com/news/singlenews/Artikel/rge-completes-lwarcel-takeover.html|archive-date=2018-10-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Sateri===\n[[Sateri]] is a viscose staple fiber producers, with a design annual production capacity of 1.4 million tonnes of viscose staple fiber.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/rge-commits-us-200-million-230000513.html | title=RGE Commits US$200 Million to Next-Generation Textile Fibre Innovation and Technology}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Sateri reported to have three mills with a combined capacity of 600,000 metric tonnes, making it the largest viscose producer in China and third largest in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theceomagazine.com/executive-interviews/resources-forestry/tey-wei-lin/|title=Tey Wei Lin CEO of Sateri|last=Johnson|first=Holly|date=2018-04-13|website=The CEO Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412035032/https://www.theceomagazine.com/executive-interviews/resources-forestry/tey-wei-lin/|archive-date=2019-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Asia Pacific Rayon===\n{{Main|Asia Pacific Rayon}}\n[[Asia Pacific Rayon]] is the first fully integrated viscose rayon producer in Asia, with a 240,000-tonne capacity mill located in [[Pangkalan Kerinci]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aprayon.com/company/about-us/|title=Asia Pacific Rayon|date=2018-10-18|access-date=2018-10-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018161857/https://www.aprayon.com/company/about-us/|archive-date=2018-10-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Pacific Oil & Gas===\nPacific Oil & Gas is an independent energy resources development company. It develops, builds, owns and operates cost-competitive projects throughout the energy supply chain.<ref name=rgeipong>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/pacific-oil-a-gas|title=Pacific Oil & Gas|publisher=Royal Golden Eagle|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004144615/http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/pacific-oil-a-gas|archive-date=2014-10-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> Concentrated on the exploration and production of oil & gas in Indonesia. Its midstream and downstream operations include an LNG receiving terminal and a Combined Cycle Gas Turbine power plant in China. In addition, it is currently developing gas-fired power plants in China, coal-fired power plants in Indonesia and an LNG export facility in Canada.<ref name=\"rgeipong\"/>\n\n==Environmental issues==\nIn 2014, Royal Golden Eagle was under considerable pressure from international environmental organisations to improve:\n\n*[[World Business Council for Sustainable Development]] told APRIL that it would be expelled from the organisation if it did not end deforestation within 12 months, noting a government estimate that 60% of its pulp came from the rainforest. It also recommended that all Royal Golden Eagle companies should be included in the commitment, not just APRIL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theecologist.org/News/news_round_up/2244890/pulp_and_paper_giant_end_deforestation.html|title=Pulp and paper giant - end deforestation!|work=The Ecologist|access-date=2014-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214112559/http://www.theecologist.org/News/news_round_up/2244890/pulp_and_paper_giant_end_deforestation.html|archive-date=2014-12-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*The [[Worldwide Fund for Nature]] (WWF) gave a cautious response to APRIL's announced Sustainable Forest Management Policy, noting that the policies did not go far enough and that previous commitments had not been honoured. It recommends that external parties should 'wait and see' before sourcing or investing in APRIL or associated businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://awsassets.wwf.or.id/downloads/wwf__31jan14__april_buyers_and_investors_advisory_en_final.pdf|title=April Buyers and Investors Advidosy|publisher=World Wide Fund for Nature|access-date=2014-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214112500/http://awsassets.wwf.or.id/downloads/wwf__31jan14__april_buyers_and_investors_advisory_en_final.pdf|archive-date=2014-12-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Greenpeace]] claimed that APRIL, along with its sister companies, \"is the greatest threat to the Indonesian rainforest\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/Six-myths-indonesias-biggest-forest-destroyer-wants-you-believe|title=Six myths Indonesia's biggest forest destroyer wants you to believe|publisher=Greenpeace|access-date=2014-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214111921/http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/Six-myths-indonesias-biggest-forest-destroyer-wants-you-believe|archive-date=2014-12-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, both Greenpeace and WWF welcomed the commitments made by RGE and APRIL to zero deforestation across their supply chains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jakartaglobe.beritasatu.com/business/forest-certification-pefc/|title=APRIL, APP Get Forest Certification from PEFC|publisher=GlobeAsia|access-date=2015-11-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151013070020/http://jakartaglobe.beritasatu.com/business/forest-certification-pefc/|archive-date=2015-10-13|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sustainablebrands.com/news_and_views/behavior_change/sustainable_brands/indonesian_pulp_paper_giant_april_pledges_zero_def|title=Indonesian Pulp and Paper Giant APRIL Pledges Zero Deforestation, Greenpeace Applauds|date=3 June 2015|publisher=Sustainable Brands|access-date=2015-12-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826175044/http://www.sustainablebrands.com/news_and_views/behavior_change/sustainable_brands/indonesian_pulp_paper_giant_april_pledges_zero_def|archive-date=2015-08-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://news.mongabay.com/2015/12/the-year-in-rainforests-2015/|title=The year in rainforests: 2015|date=29 December 2015|publisher=Mongabay|access-date=2015-12-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091103/http://news.mongabay.com/2015/12/the-year-in-rainforests-2015/|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, APRIL announced a US$100 million investment in conservation and eco-restoration of peatland in Riau, spanning 150,000 hectares.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2015/12/01/paper-corporation-step-forest-conservation.html|title=Paper corporate to step up forest conservation|publisher=The Jakarta Post|access-date=2015-12-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106084030/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2015/12/01/paper-corporation-step-forest-conservation.html|archive-date=2016-01-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/world/indonesian-firm-pledges-s141m-to-restore-peatlands|title=Indonesian firm pledges S$141m to restore peatlands|date=2 December 2015|publisher=The Straits Times|access-date=2015-12-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107144745/http://www.straitstimes.com/world/indonesian-firm-pledges-s141m-to-restore-peatlands|archive-date=2016-01-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.metrotvnews.com/read/2015/12/02/456428/april-group-invests-us-100-million-for-peat-restoration|title=April Group Invests US$100 Million for Peat Restoration|publisher=MetroTV News|access-date=2015-12-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304232209/http://en.metrotvnews.com/read/2015/12/02/456428/april-group-invests-us-100-million-for-peat-restoration|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe company and its business groups engage local communities and NGOs to develop programs for community development and fire prevention, to great success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inside-rge.com/kishore-mahbubani-reflections-RGE|title=Kishore Mahbubani: Reflections on RGE|date=September 21, 2016|website=Inside RGE|access-date=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213212953/http://www.inside-rge.com/kishore-mahbubani-reflections-RGE|archive-date=February 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 the [[Rainforest Action Network]] has named [[Asia Pacific Resources International Holdings|APRIL]] as one of Indonesia\u2019s most destructive corporations cutting [[rainforest]]s and replacing them with monoculture [[acacia]] pulp wood [[plantations]] grown on these cleared rainforests and [[peatland]]s. APRIL and another major company under separate ownership, [[Asia Pulp & Paper]], produce 80 percent of Indonesia\u2019s [[pulp and paper]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ran.org/content/app-and-april-indonesia%E2%80%99s-leaders-climate-and-rainforest-destruction#ixzz1a7JG6h4U|title=APP and APRIL: Indonesia's Leaders in Climate and Rainforest Destruction|publisher=Rainforest Action Network|date=2011-09-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015053621/http://ran.org/content/app-and-april-indonesia%E2%80%99s-leaders-climate-and-rainforest-destruction#ixzz1a7JG6h4U|archivedate=2011-10-15}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n\n===Tax evasion===\nAsian Agri was investigated for allegedly evading taxes between 2002 and 2005, which the company consistently denied.<ref name=richest2009>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2009/80/indonesia-billionaires-09_Sukanto-Tanoto_USK7.html|title=Indonesia's 40 Richest 2009|work=Forbes|date=2009-02-12|access-date=2017-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724214724/https://www.forbes.com/lists/2009/80/indonesia-billionaires-09_Sukanto-Tanoto_USK7.html|archive-date=2018-07-24|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2012, the [[Supreme Court of Indonesia]] ordered Asian Agri Group to pay Rp2.52 trillion (US$260 million) in back taxes and fines as vicarious liability,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/archive/asian-agri-ordered-to-pay-back-tax/563945/|title=Asian Agri ordered to pay back tax|work=The Jakarta Globe|date=2012-12-29|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604091230/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/archive/asian-agri-ordered-to-pay-back-tax/563945/|archive-date=2013-06-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> The company paid the back tax and in January 2014 paid the fine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/business/asian-agri-reluctantly-bows-down-to-courts-demands/|title=Asian Agri reluctantly bows down to court's demands|work=The Jakarta Globe|date=2014-02-01|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204001128/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/business/asian-agri-reluctantly-bows-down-to-courts-demands/|archive-date=2014-02-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> saying it would still file a judicial review.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iaBLHtC__6Z-4c50CklhofCTHEIw?docId=e9ca15fc-6f6a-4bdd-8aa7-f56d72496333|title=Indonesian palm oil giant Asian Agri to pay $205mn tax fine|work=AFP|date=2014-01-30}}</ref> Indonesia\u2019s [[Tempo (Indonesian magazine)|Tempo]] magazine was found guilty by the Jakarta court of defaming the company in an investigative report looking into these matters, which were published in the book [[Key Witness (book)|Key Witness]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report-2009|title=Human Rights Watch 19th annual World Report|year=2009|publisher=Human Rights Watch|page=263|access-date=2016-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026084652/https://www.hrw.org/world-report-2009|archive-date=2016-10-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Deutsche Bank controversy===\nBeckett Pte Ltd, 29% of which is indirectly owned by Sukanto Tanoto, was in legal disputes against Deutsche Bank, claiming that the bank had pledged shares, owned directly or indirectly by Beckett Pte Ltd in PT Swabara Mining and Energy, PT Asminco Bara Utama, PT Indonesia Bulk Terminal and PT Adaro Indonesia without due process and at an undervalue. Singapore's High Court found in favour of Deutsche Bank.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2007/1224/044.html|title=A new chapter|work=Forbes|date=2007-12-14|access-date=2017-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825195813/http://www.forbes.com/global/2007/1224/044.html|archive-date=2016-08-25|url-status=live}}</ref> The High Court did however state that Deutsche Bank had \"failed to discharge its duties as pledgee\" in a share sale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgei.com/files/media_releases/TODAY%20-%20Business%20Briefs%20-%2022-23Sep07.pdf|title=Business Briefs|work=TODAY|date=2007-09-22|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217101017/http://www.rgei.com/files/media_releases/TODAY%20-%20Business%20Briefs%20-%2022-23Sep07.pdf|archive-date=2014-12-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Indonesian brands]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Pulp and paper companies of Indonesia]]\n{{Portal|Indonesia}}\n", "text_old": "{{infobox company\n| name             = Royal Golden Eagle \n| logo             = \n| type             = [[Corporation|Private]]\n| genre            = \n| fate             = \n| predecessor      = \n| successor        = \n| foundation       = \n| founder          = [[Sukanto Tanoto]]\n| defunct          = \n| location_city    = [[Singapore]]\n| location_country = \n| locations        = \n| area_served      = [[World]]wide\n| key_people       = \n| industry         = [[Pulp (paper)|Pulp]], [[paper industry|paper]], [[Rayon]]\n| products         = [[Packaging]], paper, tissue, Rayon\n| services         = \n| revenue          = \n| assets           = \n| net_income       = \n| operating_income = \n| aum              = \n| equity           = \n| owner            = \n| num_employees    = \n| parent           = \n| divisions        = \n| subsid           = \n| homepage         = {{url|https://www.rgei.com/}}\n| footnotes        = \n| intl             = \n}}\n\n'''Royal Golden Eagle''' ('''RGE''', also known as '''Raja Garuda Emas''', previously '''Raja Garuda Mas''') is an integrated, resource-based industrial group in Asia Pacific, with businesses in paper, palm oil, construction and energy, property, asset management. Owned by [[Demographics of Indonesia|Indonesian]] businessman [[Sukanto Tanoto]], the group employs 60,000 people worldwide with assets exceeding [[US$]]20 billion.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.weforum.org/organizations/rge-pte-ltd/|title=RGE|website=World Economic Forum|language=en|access-date=2020-04-20}}</ref>\n\n\n\n==History==\n[[Sukanto Tanoto]] founded his first business in 1967 supplying spare parts to the oil and construction industries in Indonesia,<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.sukantotanoto.net/sukantotanoto|title=RGE Group {{!}} Indonesia Founder|website=www.sukantotanoto.net|access-date=2016-11-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170314064455/http://www.sukantotanoto.net/sukantotanoto|archive-date=2017-03-14|url-status=live}}</ref> before winning contracts in building gas pipelines for multinationals in 1972.<ref name=fortune2007>{{cite web |url=http://www.rgmi.com/index.php/component/option,com_docman/Itemid,/task,doc_download/gid,8 |title=From rags to US$2.8b fortune |work=The Business Times |date=2007-04-07 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070705183323/http://www.rgmi.com/index.php/component/option,com_docman/Itemid,/task,doc_download/gid,8 |archivedate=July 5, 2007 }}</ref> His business grew considerably following the [[1973 oil crisis]] when he open his own plywood mill in Indonesia.<ref name=\"Sukanto2009\"/> He diversified into palm oil in 1979. Since 1985, Tanoto\u2019s companies have planted 30,000 acres of palm oil plantation each year, with plantations spread over three provinces in Sumatra with a total land area of 160,000 hectares.<ref name=\"Sukanto2009\"/> He listed the public pulp and paper business [[Asia Pacific Resources International Holdings]] (APRIL) on the New York Stock Exchange in 1995, delisting it in 2001.<ref name=richest2006>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/80/06indonesia_Sukanto-Tanoto-family_USK7.html|title=Indonesia's 40 Richest 2006|work=Forbes|date=2006-07-09|access-date=2017-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161204085508/http://www.forbes.com/lists/2006/80/06indonesia_Sukanto-Tanoto-family_USK7.html|archive-date=2016-12-04|url-status=live}}</ref> The company moved its base to Singapore in 1997 in order to mitigate the effects of a global travel ban that had been placed upon Indonesia at the time.<ref name=\"Sukanto2009\"/> In 2011 APRIL became a founding member of the Indonesia Business Council for Sustainable Development.<ref name=\"aprilwebsite\"/>\n\n==Business Structure==\nFrom its base in Singapore, the company conducts activities across four business sectors: pulp and paper; agro industry; dissolving wood pulp and viscose staple fibre; and energy resource development.<ref name=\"Sukanto2009\"/>\n\n===Asia Pacific Resources International Holdings Limited (APRIL)===\nLocated in the [[Riau|Riau province]] of Indonesia, [[Asia Pacific Resources International Holdings|APRIL]] operates one of the world\u2019s largest pulp and paper mills.<ref name=sustainabilitysolution>[http://www.aprilasia.com/images/pdfs/APRIL%27s%20commitment%20to%20being%20part%20of%20the%20sustainability%20solution%20-%20by%20AJ%20Devanesan,%20COO%20APRIL.pdf \"APRIL's commitment to being part of the 'sustainability solution',\"]{{Dead link|date=April 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} Business 2020, November 2011</ref> With an annual pulp production capacity of 2.8 million tons and an annual fine paper production capacity of 820,000 tons,<ref name=rgeiapril>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/april|title=APRIL|publisher=Royal Golden Eagle|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004092531/http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/april|archive-date=2014-10-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> it generates employment opportunities for 90,000 local people and represents 6.9% of Riau Province\u2019s economic output (2009).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.aprilasia.com/images/pdfs/2011-Executive%20Summary%20Analisis%20Dampak%20in%20Bahasa%2012des%202011.pdf|title=Economic and Fiscal Impact Analysis of PT RAPP|publisher=University of Indonesia \u2013 Economic and Social Research Unit|year=2010}}{{Dead link|date=May 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n===Asia Symbol===\nEstablished in Shandong and Guangdong, China in 2005, Asia Symbol has an annual production capacity of 1.5 million tons of pulp, 450,000 tons of fine paper and 520,000 tons of paper board. Its Shandong plant operates the world\u2019s largest single pulp production line, with state-of-the-art manufacturing technology and environment protection practices.<ref name=rgeiasiasymbol>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/asia-symbol|title=Asia Symbol|publisher=Royal Golden Eagle|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004144610/http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/asia-symbol|archive-date=2014-10-04|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nBoardOne (\u535a\u65fa in Chinese) is the main brand of paperboard products produced by the Shandong mill. It includes several types of packaging, including packaging for food, tobacco, and pharmaceuticals products. BoardOne can be found in Europe, Americas, ME and Asia market. BoardOne is featured with printability, and runnability on high speed packaging lines.\n\nThere are two lines producing BoardOne products. BM11 has a web width of 3.6m, grammage range of 190-380g, main products are FBB and SBS; BM12 has a web width of 4.6m, grammage range of 170-400g, mainly LPB, cigarette packaging boards and food packaging/service boards (cup stock and cup plate etc.).\n\nThere are two pulp lines located in Shandong mill. BHKP and BSKP can be supplied internally for BoardOne board making.\n\n===Asian Agri===\n[[Asian Agri]] is one of Asia\u2019s largest [[palm oil]] producers, with an annual crude palm oil production capacity of one million tons with 28 oil palm plantations, 19 palm oil mills and 160,000 hectares of palm plantation.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgei.com/group-companies-sp-373/asian-agri|title=Asian Agri|publisher=Royal Golden Eagle|access-date=2014-12-13|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217101020/http://www.rgei.com/group-companies-sp-373/asian-agri|archive-date=2014-12-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Apical Group Limited===\n[[Apical Group|Apical]], with operations in Indonesia and China, is one Indonesia's largest exporters of palm oil with refining, processing and trading of palm oil for both domestic use and international export. The company's operations in include four refineries, a biodiesel plant and a crushing plant.<ref name=rgeiapical>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/apical|title=Apical|publisher=Royal Golden Eagle|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217100958/http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/apical|archive-date=2014-12-17|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n===Bracell Limited===\n[[Bracell Limited]] (Bracell, {{sehk|1768}}) is one of the largest specialty cellulose producers in the world. Its operations are in Brazil. It produces different grades of specialty cellulose.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bracell.com/|title=Home|website=Bracell|access-date=2019-07-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190717112530/https://www.bracell.com/|archive-date=2019-07-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIt was formerly known as Sateri Holdings Limited, which undergone a name change on February 26, 2015.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.brazilcellulose.com/phocadownload/download/document/bracell-completes-name-changee.pdf|title=Bracell Limited Completes Name Change|date=2015-11-02|access-date=2015-11-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304055144/http://www.brazilcellulose.com/phocadownload/download/document/bracell-completes-name-changee.pdf|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref> Bracell was privatized on Oct 24, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lesprom.com/en/news/Bracell_completes_1_1_billion_privatisation_75774/|title=Bracell completes $1.1 billion privatisation|website=www.lesprom.com|access-date=2019-07-24|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190716205318/https://www.lesprom.com/en/news/Bracell_completes_1_1_billion_privatisation_75774|archive-date=2019-07-16|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nRGE completed the acquisition of Lwarcel Celulose from Lwart Group on Aug 31, 2018. Lwarcel will be managed under Bracell Group.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.euwid-paper.com/news/singlenews/Artikel/rge-completes-lwarcel-takeover.html|title=RGE completes Lwarcel Celulose takeover &#124; EUWID Pulp and Paper|website=www.euwid-paper.com|access-date=2018-10-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018161844/https://www.euwid-paper.com/news/singlenews/Artikel/rge-completes-lwarcel-takeover.html|archive-date=2018-10-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Sateri===\n[[Sateri]] is a viscose staple fiber producers, with a design annual production capacity of 1.4 million tonnes of viscose staple fiber.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/rge-commits-us-200-million-230000513.html | title=RGE Commits US$200 Million to Next-Generation Textile Fibre Innovation and Technology}}</ref>\n\nIn 2018, Sateri reported to have three mills with a combined capacity of 600,000 metric tonnes, making it the largest viscose producer in China and third largest in the world.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.theceomagazine.com/executive-interviews/resources-forestry/tey-wei-lin/|title=Tey Wei Lin CEO of Sateri|last=Johnson|first=Holly|date=2018-04-13|website=The CEO Magazine|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-17|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412035032/https://www.theceomagazine.com/executive-interviews/resources-forestry/tey-wei-lin/|archive-date=2019-04-12|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n\n===Asia Pacific Rayon===\n{{Main|Asia Pacific Rayon}}\n[[Asia Pacific Rayon]] is the first fully integrated viscose rayon producer in Asia, with a 240,000-tonne capacity mill located in [[Pangkalan Kerinci]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aprayon.com/company/about-us/|title=Asia Pacific Rayon|date=2018-10-18|access-date=2018-10-18|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181018161857/https://www.aprayon.com/company/about-us/|archive-date=2018-10-18|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Pacific Oil & Gas===\nPacific Oil & Gas is an independent energy resources development company. It develops, builds, owns and operates cost-competitive projects throughout the energy supply chain.<ref name=rgeipong>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/pacific-oil-a-gas|title=Pacific Oil & Gas|publisher=Royal Golden Eagle|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141004144615/http://www.rgei.com/group-companies/pacific-oil-a-gas|archive-date=2014-10-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> Concentrated on the exploration and production of oil & gas in Indonesia. Its midstream and downstream operations include an LNG receiving terminal and a Combined Cycle Gas Turbine power plant in China. In addition, it is currently developing gas-fired power plants in China, coal-fired power plants in Indonesia and an LNG export facility in Canada.<ref name=\"rgeipong\"/>\n\n==Environmental issues==\nIn 2014, Royal Golden Eagle was under considerable pressure from international environmental organisations to improve:\n\n*[[World Business Council for Sustainable Development]] told APRIL that it would be expelled from the organisation if it did not end deforestation within 12 months, noting a government estimate that 60% of its pulp came from the rainforest. It also recommended that all Royal Golden Eagle companies should be included in the commitment, not just APRIL.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theecologist.org/News/news_round_up/2244890/pulp_and_paper_giant_end_deforestation.html|title=Pulp and paper giant - end deforestation!|work=The Ecologist|access-date=2014-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214112559/http://www.theecologist.org/News/news_round_up/2244890/pulp_and_paper_giant_end_deforestation.html|archive-date=2014-12-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*The [[Worldwide Fund for Nature]] (WWF) gave a cautious response to APRIL's announced Sustainable Forest Management Policy, noting that the policies did not go far enough and that previous commitments had not been honoured. It recommends that external parties should 'wait and see' before sourcing or investing in APRIL or associated businesses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://awsassets.wwf.or.id/downloads/wwf__31jan14__april_buyers_and_investors_advisory_en_final.pdf|title=April Buyers and Investors Advidosy|publisher=World Wide Fund for Nature|access-date=2014-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214112500/http://awsassets.wwf.or.id/downloads/wwf__31jan14__april_buyers_and_investors_advisory_en_final.pdf|archive-date=2014-12-14|url-status=live}}</ref>\n*[[Greenpeace]] claimed that APRIL, along with its sister companies, \"is the greatest threat to the Indonesian rainforest\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/Six-myths-indonesias-biggest-forest-destroyer-wants-you-believe|title=Six myths Indonesia's biggest forest destroyer wants you to believe|publisher=Greenpeace|access-date=2014-12-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141214111921/http://www.greenpeace.org.uk/Six-myths-indonesias-biggest-forest-destroyer-wants-you-believe|archive-date=2014-12-14|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, both Greenpeace and WWF welcomed the commitments made by RGE and APRIL to zero deforestation across their supply chains.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://jakartaglobe.beritasatu.com/business/forest-certification-pefc/|title=APRIL, APP Get Forest Certification from PEFC|publisher=GlobeAsia|access-date=2015-11-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151013070020/http://jakartaglobe.beritasatu.com/business/forest-certification-pefc/|archive-date=2015-10-13|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.sustainablebrands.com/news_and_views/behavior_change/sustainable_brands/indonesian_pulp_paper_giant_april_pledges_zero_def|title=Indonesian Pulp and Paper Giant APRIL Pledges Zero Deforestation, Greenpeace Applauds|date=3 June 2015|publisher=Sustainable Brands|access-date=2015-12-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826175044/http://www.sustainablebrands.com/news_and_views/behavior_change/sustainable_brands/indonesian_pulp_paper_giant_april_pledges_zero_def|archive-date=2015-08-26|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\">{{cite web|url=http://news.mongabay.com/2015/12/the-year-in-rainforests-2015/|title=The year in rainforests: 2015|date=29 December 2015|publisher=Mongabay|access-date=2015-12-30|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304091103/http://news.mongabay.com/2015/12/the-year-in-rainforests-2015/|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2015, APRIL announced a US$100 million investment in conservation and eco-restoration of peatland in Riau, spanning 150,000 hectares.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2015/12/01/paper-corporation-step-forest-conservation.html|title=Paper corporate to step up forest conservation|publisher=The Jakarta Post|access-date=2015-12-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160106084030/http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2015/12/01/paper-corporation-step-forest-conservation.html|archive-date=2016-01-06|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.straitstimes.com/world/indonesian-firm-pledges-s141m-to-restore-peatlands|title=Indonesian firm pledges S$141m to restore peatlands|date=2 December 2015|publisher=The Straits Times|access-date=2015-12-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160107144745/http://www.straitstimes.com/world/indonesian-firm-pledges-s141m-to-restore-peatlands|archive-date=2016-01-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.metrotvnews.com/read/2015/12/02/456428/april-group-invests-us-100-million-for-peat-restoration|title=April Group Invests US$100 Million for Peat Restoration|publisher=MetroTV News|access-date=2015-12-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304232209/http://en.metrotvnews.com/read/2015/12/02/456428/april-group-invests-us-100-million-for-peat-restoration|archive-date=2016-03-04|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref name=\"auto\"/>\n\nThe company and its business groups engage local communities and NGOs to develop programs for community development and fire prevention, to great success.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.inside-rge.com/kishore-mahbubani-reflections-RGE|title=Kishore Mahbubani: Reflections on RGE|date=September 21, 2016|website=Inside RGE|access-date=July 24, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170213212953/http://www.inside-rge.com/kishore-mahbubani-reflections-RGE|archive-date=February 13, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011 the [[Rainforest Action Network]] has named [[Asia Pacific Resources International Holdings|APRIL]] as one of Indonesia\u2019s most destructive corporations cutting [[rainforest]]s and replacing them with monoculture [[acacia]] pulp wood [[plantations]] grown on these cleared rainforests and [[peatland]]s. APRIL and another major company under separate ownership, [[Asia Pulp & Paper]], produce 80 percent of Indonesia\u2019s [[pulp and paper]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ran.org/content/app-and-april-indonesia%E2%80%99s-leaders-climate-and-rainforest-destruction#ixzz1a7JG6h4U|title=APP and APRIL: Indonesia's Leaders in Climate and Rainforest Destruction|publisher=Rainforest Action Network|date=2011-09-23|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111015053621/http://ran.org/content/app-and-april-indonesia%E2%80%99s-leaders-climate-and-rainforest-destruction#ixzz1a7JG6h4U|archivedate=2011-10-15}}</ref>\n\n==Controversy==\n\n===Tax evasion===\nAsian Agri was investigated for allegedly evading taxes between 2002 and 2005, which the company consistently denied.<ref name=richest2009>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/lists/2009/80/indonesia-billionaires-09_Sukanto-Tanoto_USK7.html|title=Indonesia's 40 Richest 2009|work=Forbes|date=2009-02-12|access-date=2017-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180724214724/https://www.forbes.com/lists/2009/80/indonesia-billionaires-09_Sukanto-Tanoto_USK7.html|archive-date=2018-07-24|url-status=live}}</ref> In December 2012, the [[Supreme Court of Indonesia]] ordered Asian Agri Group to pay Rp2.52 trillion (US$260 million) in back taxes and fines as vicarious liability,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/archive/asian-agri-ordered-to-pay-back-tax/563945/|title=Asian Agri ordered to pay back tax|work=The Jakarta Globe|date=2012-12-29|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130604091230/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/archive/asian-agri-ordered-to-pay-back-tax/563945/|archive-date=2013-06-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> The company paid the back tax and in January 2014 paid the fine<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/business/asian-agri-reluctantly-bows-down-to-courts-demands/|title=Asian Agri reluctantly bows down to court's demands|work=The Jakarta Globe|date=2014-02-01|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140204001128/http://www.thejakartaglobe.com/business/asian-agri-reluctantly-bows-down-to-courts-demands/|archive-date=2014-02-04|url-status=dead}}</ref> saying it would still file a judicial review.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/afp/article/ALeqM5iaBLHtC__6Z-4c50CklhofCTHEIw?docId=e9ca15fc-6f6a-4bdd-8aa7-f56d72496333|title=Indonesian palm oil giant Asian Agri to pay $205mn tax fine|work=AFP|date=2014-01-30}}</ref> Indonesia\u2019s [[Tempo (Indonesian magazine)|Tempo]] magazine was found guilty by the Jakarta court of defaming the company in an investigative report looking into these matters, which were published in the book [[Key Witness (book)|Key Witness]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.hrw.org/world-report-2009|title=Human Rights Watch 19th annual World Report|year=2009|publisher=Human Rights Watch|page=263|access-date=2016-12-04|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161026084652/https://www.hrw.org/world-report-2009|archive-date=2016-10-26|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Deutsche Bank controversy===\nBeckett Pte Ltd, 29% of which is indirectly owned by Sukanto Tanoto, was in legal disputes against Deutsche Bank, claiming that the bank had pledged shares, owned directly or indirectly by Beckett Pte Ltd in PT Swabara Mining and Energy, PT Asminco Bara Utama, PT Indonesia Bulk Terminal and PT Adaro Indonesia without due process and at an undervalue. Singapore's High Court found in favour of Deutsche Bank.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/global/2007/1224/044.html|title=A new chapter|work=Forbes|date=2007-12-14|access-date=2017-09-11|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825195813/http://www.forbes.com/global/2007/1224/044.html|archive-date=2016-08-25|url-status=live}}</ref> The High Court did however state that Deutsche Bank had \"failed to discharge its duties as pledgee\" in a share sale.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rgei.com/files/media_releases/TODAY%20-%20Business%20Briefs%20-%2022-23Sep07.pdf|title=Business Briefs|work=TODAY|date=2007-09-22|access-date=2014-09-02|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141217101017/http://www.rgei.com/files/media_releases/TODAY%20-%20Business%20Briefs%20-%2022-23Sep07.pdf|archive-date=2014-12-17|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n[[Category:Indonesian brands]]\n[[Category:Conglomerate companies of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Pulp and paper companies of Indonesia]]\n{{Portal|Indonesia}}\n", "name_user": "Can I Log In", "label": "safe", "comment": "Excess spaces", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Royal_Golden_Eagle"}
